  "prompt": "Do landlords actually call employers for background checks?",
  "response": "Yes, landlords often call employers as part of the background check process when screening potential tenants. This is done to verify the applicant's employment status and income, which helps the landlord assess the applicant's ability to pay rent on time. The process may involve confirming the applicant's job title, salary, and length of employment.\n\nHowever, not all landlords conduct such thorough background checks, as the extent of the screening process can vary depending on the landlord's policies, the rental market, and local laws. Some landlords might only ask for pay stubs or bank statements as proof of income, while others might use third-party services to perform more comprehensive background checks, including employment verification.\n\nIf you're applying for a rental property, be prepared for the landlord to contact your employer. It's a good idea to inform your employer that they may receive a call from a potential landlord to verify your employment and income.",
